### Footnotes

<span id="fn_738"></span>[253:2](sbe4544.htm#fr_742.md) Maunapada.

<span id="fn_739"></span>[254:1](sbe4544.htm#fr_743.md) *S*îlâṅka quotes a
verse which the Nâgâr*g*unîyas insert here; compare part i, p. 32, note
2.

<span id="fn_740"></span>[254:2](sbe4544.htm#fr_744.md) I take duha*m*duha
for a kind of intensive form of duha.

<span id="fn_741"></span>[254:3](sbe4544.htm#fr_745.md) This is a rather
dark verse. *S*îlâṅka, after explaining it, quotes the verse as it was
read by the Nâgâr*g*unîyas, which may be rendered thus: Respect and
honours are a great obstacle, this he should know; be the thorn small
(or) difficult to pull out, a wise man should remove it by the (means we
are about to describe).

<span id="fn_742"></span>[255:1](sbe4544.htm#fr_746.md) Literally,
horripilation. By the '&c.' the other outward signs of horror are
indicated.

<span id="fn_743"></span>[255:2](sbe4544.htm#fr_748.md) It should be kept
in mind that *G*aina monks are forbidden to use cold water, because it
is considered to possess life.

<span id="fn_744"></span>[256:1](sbe4544.htm#fr_749.md) Compare
Uttarâdhyayana IV, I, above p. 18. The same words recur below, I, 2, 3,
